<DOC><DOCNO> AP880617-0258 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-06-17-88 0105EST</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 1stAdd   06-17 0484</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Business Highlights, 1st Add,0503</SECOND><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A massive amount of confidential informationwas funneled improperly from the Defense Department to McDonnellDouglas Corp., according to a search warrant issued in a nationwideinvestigation of possible corruption involving Pentagon officialsand defense contractors.   The search warrant, disclosed Thursday, said the government isinvestigating bribery of public officials in connection with ascheme in which defense contractors got inside information fromformer government officials whom they had hired as consultants.</TEXT><DATELINE>STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   General Electric Co. says it will buyBorg-Warner Corp.'s chemical business for $2.31 billion in cash ina deal that will help Borg-Warner pay off the huge debts acquiredin going private last year.   The deal announced Thursday also will swell the size of GE'srapidly growing plastics business, which will have sales of nearly$3 billion this year.   Chicago-based Borg-Warner will use the proceeds to reduce thedebt it took on last year in a $4.7 billion leveraged buyout toavoid a takeover.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Two former top executives of Beech-NutNutritional Corp. have been sentenced to a year and a day in prisonfor distributing phony apple juice intended for babies.   U.S. District Judge Thomas Platt of Brooklyn, N.Y., also leviedfines Thursday of $100,000 against the defendants, Neils Hoyvald,54, the former president and chief executive of the company, andJohn Lavery, 56, a former vice president.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A Securities and Exchange Commission lawyerwill receive a promotion and back pay as part of a federal courtsettlement on her claim that she was threatened with dismissal forcomplaining about a sexually hostile work environment.   Also as part of the settlement announced Thursday with attorneyCatherine Broderick, who had described her office as a ``sexualplayground,'' the SEC will hire an equal employment opportunityexpert to review current commission policies on sexual harassmentand make recommendations for any needed changes.</TEXT><DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Ford Motor Co. has increased its 1988 U.S. carand truck sales forecast to 15.6 million from 15.3 million, itssecond increase since the October stock market crash, a topexecutive says.   Robert Rewey, Ford's vice president for North American sales,said Thursday that Ford increased its 1988 forecast of industrysales of imported and domestic vehicles to 10.4 million cars and5.2 million trucks for the industry, up from an earlier forecast of10.2 million cars and 5.1 million trucks.</TEXT><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   The stock market tumbled Thursday as the Dow Jones industrialaverage, which climbed 32 points in the prior two trading days,fell 37.16 to 2,094.24.   Bond prices fell by as much as $16 for every $1,000 in facevalue.   Corn futures prices soared the permissible daily limit for thethird consecutive session and soybean and oat futures advancedwhile wheat futures tumbled. The dollar fell against other majorcurrencies.</TEXT></DOC>